2 (2) There is a rebuttable presumption that the following are unreasonable requests for attorney
3 fees:
4 (a) sending more than one attorney to a deposition;
5 (b) sending more than two attorneys to an oral argument or trial;
6 (c) charging for the cost of telephone calls, faxes, library facilities, or electronic research
7 subscriptions; and
8 (d) charging an hourly rate greater than the statewide average if the attorney has not been
9 practicing for more than 10 years.
10 (3) In addition to the requirements imposed by subsections (1) and (2), when considering an award
11 of attorney fees against the state, the court shall take into consideration the hourly rate charged by the attorney
12 representing the state. If the court elects to grant a rate higher than the rate charged by the attorney
13 representing the state, the court shall provide an explanation as to why the rate charged by the state does not
14 adequately compensate the attorney for which attorney fees are requested.
15 (4) In determining the reasonableness of an award of attorney fees, a court may consider factors
16 other than those contained in this section.
